  "description": "A police officer stops you on the sidewalk. He has no warrant. He has not seen a crime. Can he still frisk you?\n\nThis episode explains Terry v. Ohio, the 1968 Supreme Court case that created the modern rule for brief street stops and weapons-only frisks based on reasonable suspicion. It is the case behind the everyday legal question: how much does an officer need before a street encounter becomes a search?\n\nWe trace the Cleveland storefront observations, the Fourth Amendment problem, the Supreme Court's 8-1 ruling, and the lasting gap between a hunch, reasonable suspicion, and proof.\n\nThis is an educational documentary, not legal advice.\n\nVisual note: this video uses AI-generated symbolic reconstructions and motion graphics. They are not authentic footage, and no real-person likeness is intended.\n\nNext episode: the phone in your pocket.",
